  "verdict": "FEASIBLE, and EASIER than the binder route. Clean gates span a wide (affinity x selectivity) region -- even at LOW binding selectivity (down to ~1x). KEY INSIGHT: the discrimination is driven by the ~2000x 2-HG CONCENTRATION DIFFERENTIAL (mutant ~mM vs normal ~uM), NOT by binding selectivity -- in normal cells alpha-KG out-competes the trace 2-HG but does not FIRE; in mutant cells 2-HG dominates. So the cell's own metabolism pre-amplifies the signal. The real REQUIREMENT is CHEMICAL SPECIFICITY (alpha-KG / succinate / L-2-HG must be NON-agonists, not just weaker binders) -- which is precedented (D2HGDH is catalytically 2-HG-specific; engineered 2-HG biosensors exist). Unlike the de novo binder (His<->Arg = two equal-abundance bulky residues, intractable, RUNG-26), 2-HG gets discrimination FOR FREE from the concentration gap. -> 2-HG RECOVERS IDH1-R132H recognition.",
  "residuals": "Feasibility/occupancy model, not a designed sensor (cf. RUNG-25 for RNA). Assumes alpha-KG is a competitive NON-agonist (a SPECIFIC sensor); a false-agonist alpha-KG would need much higher selectivity. Also needs D- vs L-2-HG chirality + succinate/glutarate cross-talk + actual sensor design (ODesign ligand model / aptamer) + in-cell validation. Recovers IDH1 RECOGNITION; coupling to apoptosis is the internal-key circuit."
